00:42:45.610 --> 00:42:47.860
And then the other reason I
think you could go further

00:42:47.860 --> 00:42:50.800
is that a common
argument that's made

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:54.035
is, well, people
thought differently

00:42:54.035 --> 00:42:57.580
then than they do now,
and so we can't judge them

00:42:57.580 --> 00:43:01.510
by the same standards that
we judge people now by.

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:02.980
But here's the thing.

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:08.380
The range of available
opinions does not change.

00:43:08.380 --> 00:43:11.680
What changes over time is the
distribution of those opinions.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:14.140
There were people at the
time those Warner Brothers

00:43:14.140 --> 00:43:17.430
cartoons were made who saw
the stereotypes as bad.

00:43:17.430 --> 00:43:19.870
Now, they weren't creating
the Warner Brothers cartoons.

00:43:19.870 --> 00:43:22.160
But I think the
danger of that is

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:26.530
it has a tendency to excuse
the racism of the past.

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:28.550
And not everybody
thought that way.

00:43:28.550 --> 00:43:31.120
I'm going to guess, for
example, that a person who

00:43:31.120 --> 00:43:37.180
saw him or herself
caricatured in 1942 or 1953

00:43:37.180 --> 00:43:40.127
might feel a little differently
than, say, a white creator who

00:43:40.127 --> 00:43:40.960
created that person.

00:43:40.960 --> 00:43:43.000
I'm just going to
hazard a guess.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.370
So I think Whoopi
Goldberg's disclaimer

00:43:45.370 --> 00:43:47.650
is important to include.

00:43:47.650 --> 00:43:48.622
I'd go further.

00:43:48.622 --> 00:43:50.080
I'd go further,
because I think you

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:52.840
want to keep this art
alive and out there,

00:43:52.840 --> 00:43:56.260
but I also think we need a
complicated relationship to it.

00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:58.730
And I think it's
hard for people to--

00:43:58.730 --> 00:44:01.810
especially for things they saw
as children-- to develop that,

00:44:01.810 --> 00:44:04.040
because you have
affection for it.

00:44:04.040 --> 00:44:05.200
It was fun watching those.

00:44:05.200 --> 00:44:08.020
Mel Blanc was great.

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:12.970
And culture that is
beautiful, that is enjoyable,

00:44:12.970 --> 00:44:16.110
that is marvelous in many
ways can also be damaging.

00:44:16.110 --> 00:44:18.645
And I think people need
to have those coexisting

00:44:18.645 --> 00:44:19.270
in their minds.

00:44:19.270 --> 00:44:20.920
And I know that's hard.

00:44:20.920 --> 00:44:22.750
And I think I have
maybe exceeded

00:44:22.750 --> 00:44:25.329
the length of my answer
here and gone on too long.

00:44:25.329 --> 00:44:25.870
So I'll stop.

00:44:25.870 --> 00:44:27.830
AUDIENCE: How could
she go further?

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:30.130
PHILIP NEL: I think
